WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.580 --> 00:00:05.730
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:09.510 --> 00:00:13.360
[ Applause ]

00:00:13.360 --> 00:00:14.940
&gt;&gt; James Billington:
Good evening everyone.

00:00:14.940 --> 00:00:19.280 position:56%
It's my great pleasure as
Librarian of Congress to welcome you

00:00:19.280 --> 00:00:25.040 position:56%
to this presentation of the John W.
Kluge Prize for Lifetime Achievement

00:00:25.040 --> 00:00:27.790
in the Study of Humanity.

00:00:27.790 --> 00:00:32.350
This award has been created through
the generosity of John Kluge,

00:00:32.350 --> 00:00:38.440
who together with his wonderful
wife, is here with us tonight.

00:00:38.440 --> 00:00:43.450
It's for a prize that
we are grateful to him,

00:00:43.450 --> 00:00:47.780
but also for much else that he
has done for the nation's library

00:00:47.780 --> 00:00:50.340 position:56%
as the founder and longtime chairman

00:00:50.340 --> 00:00:52.630
of its principal private-sector
support group,

00:00:52.630 --> 00:00:54.290 position:56%
many of whose members are here also.

00:00:54.290 --> 00:00:55.910
The James Madison Council.

00:00:55.910 --> 00:01:00.510
So, John Kluge, on behalf
of all of us, thank you.

00:01:00.510 --> 00:01:11.040
[ Applause ]

00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:15.140
This prize has been created in the
Library of Congress, so I also want

00:01:15.140 --> 00:01:18.070
to thank at the outset, the
many members of Congress

00:01:18.070 --> 00:01:21.070
who are here tonight,
especially Representative Ehlers

00:01:21.070 --> 00:01:24.500
and Senator Stevens who are the
current chair and vice chair

00:01:24.500 --> 00:01:28.910
of the Congress's oldest joint
committee of the two houses,

00:01:28.910 --> 00:01:31.800
The Joint Committee on
the Library of Congress.

00:01:31.800 --> 00:01:35.090
I also want to thank members
of the Madison Council

00:01:35.090 --> 00:01:36.870
who will be meeting tomorrow

00:01:36.870 --> 00:01:40.770
under its current distinguished
long longtime friend

00:01:40.770 --> 00:01:44.130
of the library, Chairman Ed Cox.

00:01:44.130 --> 00:01:48.140
Now, the Kluge Prize is a
unique international award.

00:01:48.140 --> 00:01:53.830
It covers all languages, all
cultures and the broad fields

00:01:53.830 --> 00:01:59.250
across cultures of the
humanities and social sciences.

00:01:59.250 --> 00:02:03.940
Disciplines conspicuously not
included in the Nobel Prizes.

00:02:03.940 --> 00:02:09.160
Tonight, we honor John Hope
Franklin, and Yu Ying-Shih,

00:02:09.160 --> 00:02:13.940
two scholars who have each produced
an enormous amount of scholarship

00:02:13.940 --> 00:02:17.790
and presented it in a
wide variety of formats

00:02:17.790 --> 00:02:21.400
to a wide variety of
grateful audiences.

00:02:21.400 --> 00:02:24.270
Each of these two has played a
leading and groundbreaking role

00:02:24.270 --> 00:02:27.470
in bringing into the mainstream
of scholarship, important

00:02:27.470 --> 00:02:30.990
and previously neglected
aspects of the history

00:02:30.990 --> 00:02:33.490
of their respective native land.

00:02:33.490 --> 00:02:38.500
Moreover, the scholarship of each
has affected both the consciousness

00:02:38.500 --> 00:02:43.310
and the conscience of a
broader public in a unique way

00:02:43.310 --> 00:02:47.370
in both cultures during the
second half of the 20th century.

00:02:47.370 --> 00:02:52.650
They have both seen, in
addition that deep values lodged

00:02:52.650 --> 00:02:57.760
at the very core of the respective
cultures, provide a basis

00:02:57.760 --> 00:03:02.720
for understanding, correcting
and moving beyond past abuse

00:03:02.720 --> 00:03:06.190 position:56%
and neglect towards a better future.

00:03:06.190 --> 00:03:08.930
Our first awardee this
evening is John Hope Franklin,

00:03:08.930 --> 00:03:12.720
who has been the leading scholar in
the second half of the 20th century

00:03:12.720 --> 00:03:18.470
in establishing African American
history as an inescapably key area

00:03:18.470 --> 00:03:21.210
in the study of the American past.

00:03:21.210 --> 00:03:26.110
He has been both a pathfinder
and a model for other scholars,

00:03:26.110 --> 00:03:30.290
for the broader public, a long
and complex history of race

00:03:30.290 --> 00:03:33.680
in this country has been
opened up over the course

00:03:33.680 --> 00:03:37.170
of 63 years by this amazing man.

00:03:37.170 --> 00:03:40.160
He has produced works
of many different types

00:03:40.160 --> 00:03:42.510
and of consistent quality.

00:03:42.510 --> 00:03:46.240
He has reached a broader audience
with a celebrated textbook,

00:03:46.240 --> 00:03:51.700
a biography, an autobiography,
and his personal leadership

00:03:51.700 --> 00:03:56.800
in a lengthy dialogue on race
that ranged all over America

00:03:56.800 --> 00:04:01.090
in the final years
of the 20th century.

00:04:01.090 --> 00:04:04.480
He has broken all records
in honorary degrees.

00:04:04.480 --> 00:04:10.030
If chemists kept track of
this, they would take due note,

00:04:10.030 --> 00:04:12.430
and he is currently
emeritus professor of history

00:04:12.430 --> 00:04:16.050
at Duke University, which was named
a center for interdisciplinary

00:04:16.050 --> 00:04:19.200
and international studies
in his honor.

00:04:19.200 --> 00:04:22.660
He provided historical depth
for the argumentation used

00:04:22.660 --> 00:04:25.170
in the landmark Supreme
Court ruling of Brown

00:04:25.170 --> 00:04:26.870
versus the Board of Education.

00:04:26.870 --> 00:04:32.480
And he is an international
as well is a national hero,

00:04:32.480 --> 00:04:33.850
having played a leading role

00:04:33.850 --> 00:04:37.120
in saving the world-wide Fulbright
Program while he was chairman

00:04:37.120 --> 00:04:39.000
of its board during a period

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:44.220
when that programs budgetary
future seemed most endangered.

00:04:44.220 --> 00:04:48.510
Dr. Franklin, it is an honor to
confer on you the Kluge Prize

00:04:48.510 --> 00:04:51.470
for lifetime achievement
in the study of humanity

00:04:51.470 --> 00:04:58.510
and I respectfully request that you
come forward to receive this award.

00:04:58.510 --> 00:05:36.500
[ Applause ]

00:05:42.240 --> 00:05:45.140
&gt;&gt; John Hope Franklin: Thank
you very much, Dr. Billington.

00:05:46.500 --> 00:05:51.820
I'm deeply honored by Mr.
Kluge, Dr. Billington,

00:05:51.820 --> 00:05:54.140
and all of my colleagues
whose confidence

00:05:54.140 --> 00:05:56.470
in my efforts have
endured to the point

00:05:56.470 --> 00:06:00.590
that they supported my
candidacy for this great honor.

00:06:00.590 --> 00:06:03.840
That the Library of Congress
played a significant role

00:06:03.840 --> 00:06:06.990
in the entire process of
selecting the recipients

00:06:06.990 --> 00:06:12.210
and administering the Kluge Award,
is not at all surprising to me.

00:06:12.210 --> 00:06:15.760
You see, I have a feeling
that the librarian of Congress

00:06:15.760 --> 00:06:19.850
and his staff have
kept a wary eye on me

00:06:19.850 --> 00:06:22.210
for the past 67 years [laugther].

00:06:22.210 --> 00:06:29.950
I came to the Library of Congress
for the first time in 1939,

00:06:29.950 --> 00:06:33.540
with every intention of rewriting
the history of the United States

00:06:33.540 --> 00:06:37.960
in a way that would
be palpably inclusive.

00:06:37.960 --> 00:06:41.270
It was not easy for a
24-year-old graduate student

00:06:41.270 --> 00:06:46.170
to persuade Willard Webb, then
the study room supervisor,

00:06:46.170 --> 00:06:51.350
that I qualified for a study
room for whatever I was doing.

00:06:51.350 --> 00:06:55.260
I succeeded in persuading
him and almost every morning

00:06:55.260 --> 00:06:59.810
for the next several months Mr.
Webb, as he made his rounds,

00:06:59.810 --> 00:07:03.950
would stop and have
a few words with me.

00:07:03.950 --> 00:07:07.600
He commented that I must be quite
interested in Thomas Jefferson

00:07:07.600 --> 00:07:11.450
since I kept his notes
on Virginia on my desk,

00:07:11.450 --> 00:07:13.930
and it was frequently open.

00:07:13.930 --> 00:07:17.560
So, one day he asked me
if I found it helpful.

00:07:17.560 --> 00:07:20.440
And I told him that
it was invaluable

00:07:20.440 --> 00:07:22.690
for what I was attempting to do.

00:07:22.690 --> 00:07:25.860
And that was to confront the
numerous missed constructions

00:07:25.860 --> 00:07:28.020
of the history of the
United States by some

00:07:28.020 --> 00:07:31.780
of the most influential
thinkers in our history.

00:07:31.780 --> 00:07:34.290
He wondered what role
Jefferson played

00:07:34.290 --> 00:07:36.730
in what I was attempting to do.

00:07:36.730 --> 00:07:41.190
I merely replied that his negative
influence was enormous [laughter].

00:07:42.740 --> 00:07:46.740 position:56%
Although the average observer did
not see beyond his obvious influence

00:07:46.740 --> 00:07:49.390
as a founding father
and as the author

00:07:49.390 --> 00:07:51.190
of the Declaration of Independence.

00:07:51.190 --> 00:07:57.090 position:56%
I was not yet prepared to share
with Mr. Webb, or indeed any others,

00:07:57.090 --> 00:08:00.740
my view of Jefferson's
enormous influence in arguing

00:08:00.740 --> 00:08:04.990
that African-Americans were
inferior to whites in many ways.

00:08:04.990 --> 00:08:06.760
Jefferson insisted, for example,

00:08:06.760 --> 00:08:11.020
that since Blacks required
less sleep than whites even

00:08:11.020 --> 00:08:13.600
after a hard day's work,
they could be induced

00:08:13.600 --> 00:08:17.950
by the slightest amusement
to sit up until midnight.

00:08:17.950 --> 00:08:22.040
Yet, he continued, since
their existence appeared

00:08:22.040 --> 00:08:27.640
to "participate more of sensation
than reflection" they were disposed

00:08:27.640 --> 00:08:33.170
to sleep when abstracted from their
diversions or unemployed in labor

00:08:33.170 --> 00:08:37.170
like an animal who is at rest.

00:08:37.170 --> 00:08:39.880
Thanks to Willard Webb
and his successors,

00:08:39.880 --> 00:08:44.370 position:56%
and thanks to Dr. Billington and his
predecessors, I've been permitted

00:08:44.370 --> 00:08:46.940
to explore the wellspring
of American history

00:08:46.940 --> 00:08:49.750
from the 17th century
to the present.

00:08:49.750 --> 00:08:53.490
Thanks also to the John W.
Kluge Center, I was able,

00:08:53.490 --> 00:08:57.410
as one of the first Kluge senior
fellows at the Library of Congress

00:08:57.410 --> 00:09:03.060
to explore even more
intensively certain aspects

00:09:03.060 --> 00:09:05.180
of recent American history.

00:09:05.180 --> 00:09:09.770
Meanwhile, I spent days at a
time, weeks at a time and months

00:09:09.770 --> 00:09:14.850
at a time enjoying the resource
of what I call this eighth wonder

00:09:14.850 --> 00:09:18.510
of the world, the Library
of Congress.

00:09:18.510 --> 00:09:22.730 position:56%
What I have found, among many other
things, has been a persistent effort

00:09:22.730 --> 00:09:25.500
on the part of some
who should know better,

00:09:25.500 --> 00:09:28.270
to explain certain
developments in American history

00:09:28.270 --> 00:09:35.070 position:56%
as the inevitable result of using,
say, Africans to play certain roles.

00:09:35.070 --> 00:09:38.400
Thus, the Jeffersonian
argument goes as follows.

00:09:38.400 --> 00:09:46.130
If a slave works hard under the
lash, he is quick to fall asleep

00:09:46.130 --> 00:09:47.810
when the lights no
longer forces them

00:09:47.810 --> 00:09:52.420
to perform certain
tasks, remarkable finding.

00:09:52.420 --> 00:09:56.740
Further, if he does not manifest
an attachment to a certain way

00:09:56.740 --> 00:10:00.680
of doing things, he's likely
to become attached by instinct

00:10:00.680 --> 00:10:03.180
to another way of doing things.

00:10:03.180 --> 00:10:06.830
Fantastic, even if elementary.

00:10:06.830 --> 00:10:11.570
Finally, since "blacks secrete
less by the kidneys and more

00:10:11.570 --> 00:10:18.080 position:56%
by the glands of the skin, they have
a strong and disagreeable odor,"

00:10:18.080 --> 00:10:20.620
to which I have added, especially

00:10:20.620 --> 00:10:23.660
since in all likelihood they
are worked in the fields

00:10:23.660 --> 00:10:28.800
or in the kitchen for 12, or
15 hours, or even more a day

00:10:28.800 --> 00:10:31.910
without an opportunity to bathe.

00:10:31.910 --> 00:10:34.320
The more I have studied
the history of our country

00:10:34.320 --> 00:10:38.500
over the last 70 years, the
clearer it has become to me,

00:10:38.500 --> 00:10:42.580
by now I have come to understand
the nature of American society,

00:10:42.580 --> 00:10:45.750
and the certainty of
many of its participants

00:10:45.750 --> 00:10:48.910
that their own position
is clear and correct.

00:10:48.910 --> 00:10:52.760
I have attempted to
re-examine the ideologies

00:10:52.760 --> 00:10:54.440
that undergird our system.

00:10:54.440 --> 00:10:59.570
I've also struggled to understand
how it is that we seek a land

00:10:59.570 --> 00:11:01.370
of freedom for the people of Europe

00:11:01.370 --> 00:11:06.130
and at the same time establish
a social and economic system

00:11:06.130 --> 00:11:10.580
that enslaved people who
happened not to be from Europe,

00:11:10.580 --> 00:11:13.760
or kept in that position.

00:11:13.760 --> 00:11:16.560
I've struggled to understand
how it is that we could fight

00:11:16.560 --> 00:11:19.780
for independence and,
at the very same time,

00:11:19.780 --> 00:11:24.520
use that newly won independence
to enslave many who had joined

00:11:24.520 --> 00:11:26.240
in the fight for independence.

00:11:26.240 --> 00:11:29.180
As a student of history,
I have attempted

00:11:29.180 --> 00:11:31.190
to explain it historically.

00:11:31.190 --> 00:11:34.940
But that explanation has not
been at all satisfactory.

00:11:34.940 --> 00:11:39.230
That has left me no alternative
but to use my knowledge of history,

00:11:39.230 --> 00:11:43.740
and whatever other knowledge and
skills I have, to present the case

00:11:43.740 --> 00:11:47.710
for change in keeping
with the express purpose

00:11:47.710 --> 00:11:51.030
of attaining the promised goals
of equality for all peoples.

00:11:51.030 --> 00:11:54.920
In this way, we can perhaps
realize the goals that grow

00:11:54.920 --> 00:11:57.330 position:56%
out of the tenants to which we claim

00:11:57.330 --> 00:12:00.050
to have been committed
from the beginning.

00:12:00.050 --> 00:12:05.410
It is a sad fact, that
it was in my generation

00:12:05.410 --> 00:12:08.420
that one witnessed the first
African-Americans achieving some

00:12:08.420 --> 00:12:11.620
recognition in the
field of scholarship.

00:12:11.620 --> 00:12:15.980
Until then, few white Americans,
even those who advocated a measure

00:12:15.980 --> 00:12:19.190
of political equality,
subscribe to the view

00:12:19.190 --> 00:12:23.110
that African-Americans had the
ability to think, either abstractly

00:12:23.110 --> 00:12:26.870
or concurrently, or to
understand and assimilate ideas

00:12:26.870 --> 00:12:29.000
that had been formulated by others.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:31.740
evidence. Much of the
20th century was spent

00:12:31.740 --> 00:12:34.710
by African-American
scholars knocking on the door

00:12:34.710 --> 00:12:38.570
of American scholarship
and seeking entry.

00:12:38.570 --> 00:12:41.690
Only here and there
did the door open,

00:12:41.690 --> 00:12:46.210
and all too often it was
opened grudgingly, if at all.

00:12:46.210 --> 00:12:50.430
It was this inability to open wide
the door of American scholarship

00:12:50.430 --> 00:12:55.770
that caused William E. B.
Du Bois to comment in 1903

00:12:55.770 --> 00:12:59.590
on his own intellectual
loneliness when he said,

00:12:59.590 --> 00:13:03.420
"I sit with Shakespeare
and he winces not.

00:13:03.420 --> 00:13:08.200
Across the color line, I move
arm in arm with Balzac and Dumas,

00:13:08.200 --> 00:13:12.270
while smiling men and welcoming
women glide in gilded halls.

00:13:12.270 --> 00:13:14.290
From out the caves of evening,

00:13:14.290 --> 00:13:18.750
the swing between the strong-limbed
earth and the tracery of starts,

00:13:18.750 --> 00:13:23.130
I summon Aristotle and
Aurelius and what soul I will,

00:13:23.130 --> 00:13:29.650 position:56%
and they have come all graciously,
with no scorn, nor or condescension.

00:13:29.650 --> 00:13:33.680
So, wed with truth, I
dwell above the veil.

00:13:33.680 --> 00:13:38.720
Is this this life you grudge
me, oh nightly America?

00:13:38.720 --> 00:13:41.340
Is this the life you long to change

00:13:41.340 --> 00:13:45.420
into the dull red hideousness
of Georgia?

00:13:45.420 --> 00:13:49.830 position:56%
Are you so afraid lest peering from
this high Pisgah, between Philistine

00:13:49.830 --> 00:13:54.550
and Amalekite, we sight
the promised land?"

00:13:54.550 --> 00:14:00.470
But it is not enough merely to cite
the promised land in the distance.

00:14:00.470 --> 00:14:01.800
And Du Bois would be the first

00:14:01.800 --> 00:14:05.230
to be dissatisfied with
such a modest goal.

00:14:05.230 --> 00:14:07.330
He insisted always that the people

00:14:07.330 --> 00:14:11.150
from whom he spoke should never
be satisfied with something

00:14:11.150 --> 00:14:13.630
so ephemeral as a promised land.

00:14:13.630 --> 00:14:16.730
And when he reached the
conclusion that the land

00:14:16.730 --> 00:14:22.170
of his birth would never concede
full and equal citizenship for him,

00:14:22.170 --> 00:14:27.720 position:56%
he renounced it, the country, and
denounced it and retreated to Ghana,

00:14:27.720 --> 00:14:31.910
where he spent the
remaining few years of life.

00:14:31.910 --> 00:14:34.420
But we, who are dissatisfied
with the present condition

00:14:34.420 --> 00:14:38.880
in this country, should not
retreat to Ghana or somewhere else.

00:14:38.880 --> 00:14:41.700
Nor should we even desire to do so.

00:14:41.700 --> 00:14:48.070
Our past is here, our lord is
here, our presence is here.

00:14:48.070 --> 00:14:52.040
Our investment of more than
three centuries is here.

00:14:52.040 --> 00:14:54.910
Our future is here.

00:14:54.910 --> 00:14:58.660
Many years ago, I discovered
that there were various ways

00:14:58.660 --> 00:15:02.190
that a historian could utilize
his training and talents

00:15:02.190 --> 00:15:05.340
to move this nation closer
to the principles for which

00:15:05.340 --> 00:15:08.860
so many have made the
supreme sacrifice to achieve.

00:15:08.860 --> 00:15:12.830
So, in 1948 Thurgood
Marshall, the Chief Counsel

00:15:12.830 --> 00:15:17.510
for the NAACP legal defense fund,
sought my assistance in breaking

00:15:17.510 --> 00:15:21.140
that color barrier at the
University of Kentucky.

00:15:21.140 --> 00:15:25.490 position:56%
A young African-American was seeking
admission to do graduate work

00:15:25.490 --> 00:15:29.070
in history at the University
of Kentucky.

00:15:29.070 --> 00:15:34.700
When he was denied admission;
surprise, surprise, Marshall sued,

00:15:34.700 --> 00:15:38.280
and asked me to serve as an
expert witness in the effort

00:15:38.280 --> 00:15:40.540
to establish the fact
that the University

00:15:40.540 --> 00:15:43.970
of Kentucky was the only
publicly supported institution

00:15:43.970 --> 00:15:47.580
where you could secure
graduate training in history.

00:15:47.580 --> 00:15:50.050
Before I could testify
regarding the inadequacy

00:15:50.050 --> 00:15:52.330
of Kentucky's historically
black college

00:15:52.330 --> 00:15:54.320
in training graduate
students in history,

00:15:54.320 --> 00:15:56.800
the federal judge had
ordered the admission

00:15:56.800 --> 00:15:58.930
of the African-American
graduate student

00:15:58.930 --> 00:16:01.390
to the University of Kentucky.

00:16:01.390 --> 00:16:04.930
Even without my public
participation in the argument,

00:16:04.930 --> 00:16:08.440
I discovered that my role as
an expert witness could assist

00:16:08.440 --> 00:16:12.250
in bringing about change
and equity in our society.

00:16:12.250 --> 00:16:16.700 position:56%
And this will be done without
compromising my scholarship one wit.

00:16:16.700 --> 00:16:20.280
Some years later a variation
of the same was true in Brown

00:16:20.280 --> 00:16:22.930
versus the Board of
Education, when I discovered

00:16:22.930 --> 00:16:27.090
that I could use my training and
my knowledge to assist counsel

00:16:27.090 --> 00:16:30.130
in gaining the admission of Linda
Brown and the other plaintiffs

00:16:30.130 --> 00:16:34.340
to better schools that were
not segregated in 1954.

00:16:34.340 --> 00:16:37.940
Then, some years later,
in 1965 I discovered

00:16:37.940 --> 00:16:40.980
in the Selma Montgomery march,
that I could be effective

00:16:40.980 --> 00:16:45.170
in joining other historians as well
as crusaders of various stripes

00:16:45.170 --> 00:16:49.730
in marching and working together
to impress high and arrogant powers

00:16:49.730 --> 00:16:52.810
and to relent in their extreme
and excessive use of racial

00:16:52.810 --> 00:16:58.080
and social bigotry in their
effort to maintain the status quo.

00:16:58.080 --> 00:17:01.540
I've been most fortunate in having
the opportunity to participate

00:17:01.540 --> 00:17:04.590
