00:22:51.130 --> 00:22:57.700
After much reflection, however,
I have come to the realization

00:22:57.700 --> 00:23:02.470
that the main justification
for my presence here tonight is

00:23:02.470 --> 00:23:05.590
that both the Chinese
cultural tradition

00:23:05.590 --> 00:23:08.220
and Chinese intellectual history

00:23:08.220 --> 00:23:14.200
as a discipline are
being honored through me.

00:23:14.200 --> 00:23:19.650
The former has been the subject
of my lifetime scholarly pursuit,

00:23:19.650 --> 00:23:25.240
and the latter my chosen
field of specialization.

00:23:25.240 --> 00:23:30.010
When I first became seriously
interested in the study

00:23:30.010 --> 00:23:35.110
of Chinese history and
culture in the 1940s,

00:23:35.110 --> 00:23:38.970
the Chinese historical
mind happened to be cast

00:23:38.970 --> 00:23:43.770
in an anti-traditionalistic mold.

00:23:43.770 --> 00:23:49.710
The Chinese past as a whole,
was viewed negatively,

00:23:49.710 --> 00:23:56.290
and whatever appeared to be
uniquely Chinese was interpreted

00:23:56.290 --> 00:24:01.060
as a deviation from the norm
of civilization's progress

00:24:01.060 --> 00:24:07.930
as exemplified in the historical
development of the West.

00:24:07.930 --> 00:24:12.650
Needless to say, I
was at a complete loss

00:24:12.650 --> 00:24:17.430
as to the Chinese cultural
identity, and for that matter,

00:24:17.430 --> 00:24:20.970
also my personal identity.

00:24:20.970 --> 00:24:26.850
It was my good fortune that I was
able to finish my college education

00:24:26.850 --> 00:24:31.580
in Hong Kong and pursued
my graduate studies

00:24:31.580 --> 00:24:36.970
in the United States,
now my adopted country.

00:24:36.970 --> 00:24:42.620
As my intellectual horizon
gradually widened over the years,

00:24:42.620 --> 00:24:45.960
the truth was beginning
to dawn on me

00:24:45.960 --> 00:24:51.370
that the Chinese culture
must be clearly recognized

00:24:51.370 --> 00:24:58.060
as an indigenous tradition with
characteristics distinctly its own.

00:24:58.060 --> 00:25:00.780
The crystallization
of Chinese culture

00:25:00.780 --> 00:25:04.670
into its definitive shape
took place in the time

00:25:04.670 --> 00:25:10.230
of Confucius a crucial moment in
the ancient world better known

00:25:10.230 --> 00:25:15.210
in the West as the Axial Age.

00:25:15.210 --> 00:25:20.870
During this period, it has been
observed, a spiritual awakening

00:25:20.870 --> 00:25:26.260
or breakthrough occurred in
several highly-developed cultures

00:25:26.260 --> 00:25:31.440
in the ancient world
including China, India,

00:25:31.440 --> 00:25:35.660
Persia, Israel, and Greece.

00:25:35.660 --> 00:25:39.880
It took the form of either
philosophical reasoning

00:25:39.880 --> 00:25:45.220
or post-mythical religious
imagination or, as in the case

00:25:45.220 --> 00:25:51.390
of China, a mixed type
of moral, philosophic

00:25:51.390 --> 00:25:55.250
and religious consciousness.

00:25:55.250 --> 00:26:00.440
The awakening led directly to
the emergence of the dichotomy

00:26:00.440 --> 00:26:04.110
between the actual world
and the world beyond.

00:26:04.110 --> 00:26:08.960
The world beyond as a new vision,
provided the thinking individuals,

00:26:08.960 --> 00:26:14.630
be they philosophers,
prophets or sages

00:26:14.630 --> 00:26:17.640
with the necessary
transcending point

00:26:17.640 --> 00:26:23.470
from which the actual world
could be examined and questioned;

00:26:23.470 --> 00:26:26.660
critically as well as reflectively.

00:26:26.660 --> 00:26:28.800
This is generally known

00:26:28.800 --> 00:26:33.950
as the original transcendence
of the Axial Age.

00:26:33.950 --> 00:26:38.190
As a result of the Chinese
original transcendence in the time

00:26:38.190 --> 00:26:45.410
of Confucius, the all-important
idea of Tao emerged as a symbol

00:26:45.410 --> 00:26:52.050
of the world beyond vis-a-vis the
actual world of everyday life.

00:26:52.050 --> 00:26:56.790
But the Chinese transcendental
world of Tao and the actual world

00:26:56.790 --> 00:27:03.890 position:56%
of everyday life were conceived from
the very beginning to be related

00:27:03.890 --> 00:27:08.530
to each other in a way different

00:27:08.530 --> 00:27:14.780
from other ancient cultures
undergoing the Axial breakthrough.

00:27:14.780 --> 00:27:20.760 position:56%
For example, there is nothing in the
early Chinese philosophical visions

00:27:20.760 --> 00:27:27.500
that suggests Plato's conception
of an unseen eternal world

00:27:27.500 --> 00:27:32.810
of which the actual world
is only a pale copy.

00:27:32.810 --> 00:27:38.210 position:56%
In the religious tradition, the
world of God and the world of humans

00:27:38.210 --> 00:27:44.670
as demonstrated in the
Christian type, is also absent.

00:27:44.670 --> 00:27:49.620 position:56%
Nor, do we find in classical Chinese
thought, in all its varieties,

00:27:49.620 --> 00:27:56.850 position:56%
anything that closely resembles the
radical negativity of early Buddhism

00:27:56.850 --> 00:28:00.650
with its insistence
on the un-realness

00:28:00.650 --> 00:28:04.990
and worthlessness of this world.

00:28:04.990 --> 00:28:09.130
By contrast, the world
of Tao was not perceived

00:28:09.130 --> 00:28:11.200
as very far from the human world.

00:28:11.200 --> 00:28:18.380
As best expressed by Confucius,
"The Tao is not far from man.

00:28:18.380 --> 00:28:22.930
When a man pursues the Tao
and remains away from man,

00:28:22.930 --> 00:28:26.170
his course cannot be
considered the Tao."

00:28:26.170 --> 00:28:33.350
The notion of Tao was also
shared by all the major thinkers

00:28:33.350 --> 00:28:39.570
in the Chinese Axial Age, including
Lao Tzu, Mo Tzu and Chuang Tzu.

00:28:39.570 --> 00:28:43.050
It was their common belief
that Tao is hidden and

00:28:43.050 --> 00:28:50.500
yet functions everywhere in the
human world; even men and women

00:28:50.500 --> 00:29:01.670
of simple intelligence can know
and practice it in everyday life

00:29:01.670 --> 00:29:04.910
to a larger or lesser degree.

00:29:04.910 --> 00:29:07.640
Indeed, judging from
the ever-growing

00:29:07.640 --> 00:29:14.610
and deepening influences of the
ideas originating in the Axial Age,

00:29:14.610 --> 00:29:19.390
especially Confucian and
Taoist ideas, on all aspects

00:29:19.390 --> 00:29:23.920
of Chinese life down
through the centuries.

00:29:23.920 --> 00:29:30.980
It may not be too much an
exaggeration to suggest that Tao

00:29:30.980 --> 00:29:34.540
and history constitute the inside

00:29:34.540 --> 00:29:38.980
and the outside of
Chinese civilization.

00:29:38.980 --> 00:29:43.000
Taking the Chinese cultural
tradition to be essentially one

00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:47.280
of indigenous tradition
and independent growth,

00:29:47.280 --> 00:29:50.440
I have tried over the decades

00:29:50.440 --> 00:29:54.390
to study Chinese history
along two main lines.

00:29:54.390 --> 00:29:59.110
First, the Chinese culture must
be understood in its own terms,

00:29:59.110 --> 00:30:04.610
but at the time also in a
comparative perspective.

00:30:04.610 --> 00:30:12.290
By comparative perspective, I
refer to both Indian Buddhism

00:30:12.290 --> 00:30:14.810
in the early imperial period

00:30:14.810 --> 00:30:19.530
and Western culture
since the 16th century.

00:30:19.530 --> 00:30:21.420
Since the beginning
of the 20th century,

00:30:21.420 --> 00:30:26.720
the Chinese mind has been largely
preoccupied with the problematique

00:30:26.720 --> 00:30:29.460
of China-versus-the-West.

00:30:29.460 --> 00:30:33.900
To interpret the Chinese
past solely in its own terms

00:30:33.900 --> 00:30:39.470
without a comparative perspective
would certainly run the risk

00:30:39.470 --> 00:30:44.610
of falling into the age-old
trap of Sino centrism.

00:30:44.610 --> 00:30:49.680
Second, in my study of Chinese
history from classical antiquity

00:30:49.680 --> 00:30:56.940
to the 20th century, my focus
has always been placed on periods

00:30:56.940 --> 00:31:04.260
of change when one historical
stage moved to the next.

00:31:04.260 --> 00:31:09.150
Compared to other civilizations,
China's is particularly marked

00:31:09.150 --> 00:31:12.220
by its long historical continuity.

00:31:12.220 --> 00:31:18.370
But continuity and change went
hand-in-hand in Chinese history.

00:31:18.370 --> 00:31:22.400
Therefore, the purpose I
have set myself is twofold.

00:31:22.400 --> 00:31:25.630
Firstly, to identify
the major intellectual,

00:31:25.630 --> 00:31:29.590
social and culture changes
in the Chinese past.

00:31:29.590 --> 00:31:36.410
And, secondly, to discern if at
all possible, the unique pattern

00:31:36.410 --> 00:31:39.230
of Chinese historical changes.

00:31:39.230 --> 00:31:44.050
More often than not, such
broad and profound changes

00:31:44.050 --> 00:31:50.170
in Chinese history transcended the
rise and the fall of dynasties.

00:31:50.170 --> 00:31:55.730
Thus, the notion of dynastic cycle,
long held in traditional China,

00:31:55.730 --> 00:32:02.890
but also briefly in vogue in
the West, is highly misleading.

00:32:02.890 --> 00:32:07.570
In the early years of the 20th
century, Chinese historians began

00:32:07.570 --> 00:32:12.030
to reconstruct and re-interpret
the Chinese past according

00:32:12.030 --> 00:32:15.490 position:56%
to the historical model of the West.

00:32:15.490 --> 00:32:18.750
Since then, it has
been generally assumed

00:32:18.750 --> 00:32:22.110
that China must have
undergone similar stages

00:32:22.110 --> 00:32:27.460
of historical development as
shown in European history.

00:32:27.460 --> 00:32:30.010
In the first half of
the 20th century,

00:32:30.010 --> 00:32:34.470
Chinese historians adopted
the earlier European schemes

00:32:34.470 --> 00:32:39.470
of periodization by dividing
Chinese history into ancient,

00:32:39.470 --> 00:32:43.900
medieval and modern periods.

00:32:43.900 --> 00:32:48.560
This has been replaced since 1949

00:32:48.560 --> 00:32:53.510
by the Marxist-Stalinist
five-stage formulation.

00:32:53.510 --> 00:33:00.200
The latter remains the orthodox
in China up to this day,

00:33:00.200 --> 00:33:05.470
at least in theory if
not always in practice.

00:33:05.470 --> 00:33:12.510
This Procrustean approach, whatever
merits it may have otherwise,

00:33:12.510 --> 00:33:17.110
cannot possibly do full
justice to Chinese culture

00:33:17.110 --> 00:33:20.440
as an indigenous tradition.

00:33:20.440 --> 00:33:23.420
Only by focusing on the
unique course and shape

00:33:23.420 --> 00:33:26.770
of Chinese historical
changes, I am convinced,

00:33:26.770 --> 00:33:33.190
can we hope to see more clearly how
that great cultural tradition moved

00:33:33.190 --> 00:33:38.730
from stage to stage driven,
mainly if not entirely,

00:33:38.730 --> 00:33:41.800
by its internal dynamics.

00:33:41.800 --> 00:33:46.550
Now, let me turn to the question
of how, as two different systems

00:33:46.550 --> 00:33:51.750
of values, does Chinese culture
stand vis-a-vis Western culture

00:33:51.750 --> 00:33:54.740
in historical perspective?

00:33:54.740 --> 00:33:58.680
My earliest exposure to this
question occurred in the late 1940s

00:33:58.680 --> 00:34:04.190
when the problematique of China
versus-the-West, mentioned earlier,

00:34:04.190 --> 00:34:06.890
dominated the Chinese
intellectual world.

00:34:06.890 --> 00:34:13.730
It has not been out of my
consciousness ever since.

00:34:13.730 --> 00:34:20.750
Living in the United
States for half a century,

00:34:20.750 --> 00:34:26.510
the question has acquired a truly
existential meaning for my life

00:34:26.510 --> 00:34:31.930
as I move between the two
cultures from moment to moment.

00:34:31.930 --> 00:34:36.600 position:56%
With some initial psychological
readjustments, I have long been able

00:34:36.600 --> 00:34:38.010
to enjoy the American way

00:34:38.010 --> 00:34:43.710
of life while still retaining
my Chinese cultural identity.

00:34:43.710 --> 00:34:47.270
However, the best guide with regard

00:34:47.270 --> 00:34:51.090
to whether Chinese culture is
compatible with the core values

00:34:51.090 --> 00:34:55.740
of the West can only be
provided by Chinese history.

00:34:55.740 --> 00:35:00.170
China first encountered the modern
West at the end of the 16th century

00:35:00.170 --> 00:35:04.720
when the Jesuits came to do their
missionary work in East Asia.

00:35:04.720 --> 00:35:09.290
The culturally sensitive Matteo
Ricci was very quick to discover

00:35:09.290 --> 00:35:11.600
that the Chinese religious
atmosphere

00:35:11.600 --> 00:35:17.700
at that time was highly
tolerant; Confucianism, Buddhism

00:35:17.700 --> 00:35:22.380
and Taoism were generally
regarded as one and the same thing.

00:35:22.380 --> 00:35:27.300
It was this period of religious
tolerance that accounted

00:35:27.300 --> 00:35:32.300
for Ricci's extraordinary
success in his conversion

00:35:32.300 --> 00:35:37.840
of many leading members
of the Confucian elite.

00:35:37.840 --> 00:35:41.630
The Confucian faith in
the sameness of human mind

00:35:41.630 --> 00:35:44.390
and the universal accessibility
of Tao

00:35:44.390 --> 00:35:49.230
to every human person anywhere
led some Chinese converts

00:35:49.230 --> 00:35:53.940
to promote a synthesis of
Christianity with Confucianism.

00:35:53.940 --> 00:35:59.920
The Chinese Tao was now further
expanded to include Christianity.

00:35:59.920 --> 00:36:05.360
In the late 19th century, it was
also the open-minded Confucians

00:36:05.360 --> 00:36:08.770 position:56%
who enthusiastically embraced values

00:36:08.770 --> 00:36:12.450
and ideas dominant
in the modern West.

00:36:12.450 --> 00:36:18.250
Such as democracy, liberty,
equality, rule of law,

00:36:18.250 --> 00:36:24.550
autonomy of the individual person,
and, above all, human rights.

00:36:24.550 --> 00:36:29.000
When some of them visited Europe
or America for the first time

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:34.580
and stayed there long enough to
make first-hand observations,

00:36:34.580 --> 00:36:39.460
they were all deeply impressed,
first of all, by the ideals

00:36:39.460 --> 00:36:45.080
and institutions of Western
constitutional democracy.

00:36:45.080 --> 00:36:51.350
At the turn of the century, there
were two rival Confucian schools

00:36:51.350 --> 00:36:56.800
in China known as the New Text
and the Old Text, respectively.

00:36:56.800 --> 00:37:04.030
Both advocated democracy and
jointly began a systematic search

00:37:04.030 --> 00:37:07.540
for the origins and the
evolution of democratic ideas

00:37:07.540 --> 00:37:09.790
in early Confucian texts.

00:37:09.790 --> 00:37:15.580
In so doing, it is clear that
they took the compatibility

00:37:15.580 --> 00:37:17.910
between Chinese culture
and Western culture

00:37:17.910 --> 00:37:21.890
as two systems of values
for granted.

00:37:21.890 --> 00:37:28.030
Last but not least, I wish to
say a word about human rights.

00:37:28.030 --> 00:37:33.650
Like democracy, human rights as
a term is linguistically specific

00:37:33.650 --> 00:37:40.260
to the West and nonexistent in
traditional Confucian discourse.

00:37:40.260 --> 00:37:46.330
However, if we agree that the
concept of human rights as defined

00:37:46.330 --> 00:37:52.320
in the United Nations'
Universal Declaration of 1948,

00:37:52.320 --> 00:37:55.870
is predicated on the
double recognition

00:37:55.870 --> 00:38:00.640
of a common humanity
and human dignity.

00:38:00.640 --> 00:38:07.570
Then we are also justified to speak
of a Confucian idea of human rights

00:38:07.570 --> 00:38:11.930
without the Western terminology.

00:38:11.930 --> 00:38:16.200
Recognition of common
humanity and respect

00:38:16.200 --> 00:38:22.570
for human dignity are both clearly
articulated in the Analects,

00:38:22.570 --> 00:38:25.850
Mencius and other early texts.

00:38:25.850 --> 00:38:32.130
It is remarkable that by the first
century Common Era, at the latest,

00:38:32.130 --> 00:38:36.270
the Confucian notion of human
dignity was openly referred

00:38:36.270 --> 00:38:44.270 position:56%
to in imperial decrees as sufficient
grounds for the prohibition

00:38:44.270 --> 00:38:47.920
of the sale or killing of slaves.

00:38:47.920 --> 00:38:59.310
Both imperial decrees, dated 9
and 35 Common Era, respectively,

00:38:59.310 --> 00:39:02.920
cited the same famous
Confucian dictum,

00:39:02.920 --> 00:39:09.640
"Of all living things
produced by Heaven and Earth,

00:39:09.640 --> 00:39:14.530
the human person is the noblest."

00:39:14.530 --> 00:39:18.550
Slavery as an institution
was never accepted

00:39:18.550 --> 00:39:22.280
by Confucianism as legitimate.

00:39:22.280 --> 00:39:28.960
It was the Confucian humanism that
predisposed late Ch'ing Confucians

00:39:28.960 --> 00:39:33.720
to be so readily appreciative
of the Western theory

00:39:33.720 --> 00:39:37.910
and practice of human rights.

00:39:37.910 --> 00:39:44.590
If history is any guide, then
there seems to be a great deal

00:39:44.590 --> 00:39:48.520
of overlapping consensus
in basic values

00:39:48.520 --> 00:39:52.050
between Chinese culture
and Western culture.

00:39:52.050 --> 00:39:57.250
After all, recognition
of common humanity

00:39:57.250 --> 00:40:05.100
and human dignity is what the
Chinese Tao has been about.

00:40:05.100 --> 00:40:11.080
I am more convinced than ever
that once Chinese culture returns

00:40:11.080 --> 00:40:15.670
to the main flow of
Tao, the problematique

00:40:15.670 --> 00:40:21.070
of China-versus-the-West
will also come to an end.

00:40:21.070 --> 00:40:22.870
Thank you.

